Like a ton of other people here, the watermarks made me a member!  LOL  I am one of the people who is always saying -thank the uploader, people!!- and I still mean it. And, I don't think the bad language is called for.  .......ok...now that's out of the way.  

UPLOADER - THIS PART IS FOR YOU:  You see what's happened, right?  People hate you now and whatever it was that you were pushing through those horrible adverts will not be bought, seen, whatever.  I did look at the screenshot and it's ridiculous.  

Here's what you could have done --because, YES, you do deserve credit for your work, A brief promotion/sinage on the screen at the start, perhaps as the movie studio logos show up along with one at the end.  You could also do what the studios themselves do when they submit the films for awards and do semi-transparant watermarks discreetly, meaning top right, bottom, etc. not over the actors themselves and not in red, etc.  And, only a few times..meaning 3, max, during the film.  

Had you done this, you would see three pages of praise here instead of insults (whether they were over the top or not).  That's what you want, right?  You spent time offering up something for free and it looks like you did a good job.  No one is talking about that.  No one is asking, where can I get more.  Or saying, please...upload more.  Or...what else do you do or offer...which is where an opening to a possibility to make money might come in, because most of us have or want jobs: that's not a sin.

So, just take the lesson and your licks and next time follow the guidelines I suggested and I bet you get a great reaction.  I'm not an expert in movies, but I am one in promotion.  If I saw your screenshot and the quality was horrible, or the A/V ratings were crap, I wouldn't take the time to write this post, but it sounds like you're a talented person who got a little over zealous after spending a lot of time on a great product that you were set to give away.

Thank you uploader.  I hope we see more from you... sans over the top watermarks, but certainly with some information on where we might see more of your material. :-)
